S7.T1.9.table:
Runtime (sec)  Size (MBytes)  F-measure
BSS 34.0334.0334.03 47.1147.1147.11 1.01.01.0
HSS 60557.9360557.9360557.93 1257.061257.061257.06 1.01.01.0
SSS 34.0334.0334.03 47.1547.1547.15 1.01.01.0
references:
Table 1 shows the runtime and memory size
required and the F-measure results
achieved with the three secure summation protocols.
As can be seen, the HSS requires significantly higher
runtime and memory (which is not practical in real applications)
to improve privacy against collusion attacks on the BSS
without compromising the F-measure results.
However, the
SSS approach
requires similar runtime and memory as the BSS
for improving privacy against collusions with no loss
in linkage quality.
We therefore use SSS in all following experiments.
